-- South African Stocks Advance, Led by AVI, BHP Billiton, Metmar and Sanyati
-- B y   G a r t h   T h e u n i s s e n   a n d   C a r l i   L o u r e n s
-- 2010-10-20T15:40:49Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-20/south-african-equities-rise-for-second-day-in-three-billiton-merafe-move.html
South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  rose 77.42, or 0.3 percent, to 30,080.50 at the 5
p.m. close in Johannesburg.  The following are among the most active stocks in the South
African market.  AVI Ltd.  (AVI SJ), the producer and distributor of consumer
goods including food and cosmetics, rose to the highest since
August 1990, adding 80 cents, or 2.9 percent, to 28 rand. The
company said its operating performance for the three months
through September was “materially ahead of the corresponding
period last year.”  BHP Billiton Plc (BIL SJ) gained 4.75 rand, or 2 percent,
to 239.10 rand. The world’s largest mining company reported a 6
percent increase in first-quarter iron-ore production and said
petroleum production rose to a record.  Separately Canadian province Saskatchewan rejected an offer
of C$370 million ($358 million) of infrastructure investment
from BHP, which is trying to win support for its $40 billion bid
for Potash Corp. of Saskatchewan Inc.  Metmar Ltd.  (MML SJ), the mining investor and metals
trader, surged to a more-than one-year high, climbing 40 cents,
or 9.8 percent, to 4.50 rand. The company said it started talks,
without giving further details, according to a regulatory
statement to Johannesburg’s stock exchange today.  Sanyati Holdings Ltd.  (SAN SJ), a civil engineering and
construction company, gained 2 cents, or 4.7 percent, to 45
cents, the highest level since Oct. 1. The company said it
expects earnings per share to be between 45 percent and 50
percent higher in the six months through August compared to the
corresponding period the previous year.  Value Group Ltd.  (VLE SJ), a South African transport
company, rose 5 cents, or 1.4 percent, to 3.65 rand. The company
said revenue rose 17 percent to 740.8 million rand in the six-
months to end-August.  To contact the reporters on this story:
